# OSI Model

## Overview

The OSI Model (Open Systems Interconnection Model) is a conceptual framework used to understand how data travels across a network.

It divides network communication into **seven layers**, where each layer has a specific responsibility.

This layered approach helps standardize communication between different systems and technologies.

---

# The 7 Layers of the OSI Model

The OSI model contains seven layers, starting from the physical transmission of data up to the applications used by users.

1. Physical
2. Data Link
3. Network
4. Transport
5. Session
6. Presentation
7. Application

A common way to remember the order is:

**"Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away."**

---

# Layer 1 – Physical

The Physical layer is responsible for transmitting raw bits over a physical medium.

Examples include:

- Ethernet cables
- Fiber optic cables
- Wireless signals

This layer deals with hardware components and the electrical signals used to transmit data.

---

# Layer 2 – Data Link

The Data Link layer ensures reliable data transfer between devices on the same network.

It is responsible for:

- MAC addressing
- detecting transmission errors
- packaging data into frames

Technologies operating at this layer include:

- switches
- network interface cards (NIC)

---

# Layer 3 – Network

The Network layer handles logical addressing and routing of data between networks.

It determines the best path for data to travel.

The main protocol used at this layer is:

- IP (Internet Protocol)

Devices operating here include:

- routers

---

# Layer 4 – Transport

The Transport layer ensures reliable communication between devices.

Its responsibilities include:

- breaking data into smaller segments
- controlling data flow
- ensuring reliable delivery

Two common protocols used here are:

- TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
- UDP (User Datagram Protocol)

TCP focuses on reliability, while UDP focuses on speed.

---

# Layer 5 – Session

The Session layer manages communication sessions between devices.

It is responsible for:

- establishing sessions
- maintaining connections
- terminating sessions

This layer ensures that communication between systems stays organized.

---

# Layer 6 – Presentation

The Presentation layer is responsible for formatting and translating data.

It ensures that data sent from one system can be understood by another.

Common tasks include:

- data encoding
- encryption
- compression

---

# Layer 7 – Application

The Application layer is the layer closest to the user.

It provides network services directly to applications.

Examples include:

- HTTP (web browsing)
- FTP (file transfer)
- SMTP (email services)
- DNS (domain name resolution)

---

# Why the OSI Model is Important

The OSI model helps network engineers and security professionals understand how data flows through a network.

It also makes troubleshooting easier by isolating problems within specific layers.

---

# Key Takeaways

- The OSI Model divides network communication into seven layers.
- Each layer performs a specific role in the data transmission process.
- The model helps standardize communication between different systems.
- Understanding the OSI model is important for networking and cybersecurity.

